> Is it safe to change this occurrence of `src.get()` in pybind11 to `*src` since most custom holder types will have `operator*`.

Nope; because `.get()` returns the owned pointer which may be null and doesn't dereference it.

In theory, I guess, we could abstract this away, e.g. via specialization (with specializations provided for standard library holders like `unique_ptr` and `shared_ptr`), so you could do something like

```cpp
template<typename Actor> struct pybind11::detail::holder_getter<PointerHolder<Actor>> {
    Actor* get(PointerHolder<Actor>& holder) {
        return holder.getPointer();
    }
}
```

Something weird must be happening in Qt internals because in this tiny example, the missing copy constructor gets caught at compile time rather than causing a crash at run time:

```c++
#include <functional>

#include <pybind11/pybind11.h>
#include <pybind11/functional.h>

namespace py = pybind11;

class UncopyableClass {
    UncopyableClass(const UncopyableClass &);
    UncopyableClass &operator=(const UncopyableClass &);
public:
    UncopyableClass() {}
};

PYBIND11_PLUGIN(example) {
    py::module m("example", "pybind11 bug exaple");

    // Uncopyable class can still be instantiated from python
    py::class_<UncopyableClass> UncopyableClass_class(m, "UncopyableClass");
    UncopyableClass_class.def(py::init<>());

    // This will fail on compile
    m.def("send_uncopyable", [](std::function<void(UncopyableClass)> cb) {
        UncopyableClass uncopyable;
        cb(uncopyable);
    });

    return m.ptr();
}
```

Will also work fine if I pass through an `UncopyableClass *` instead! So perhaps there may be something I can do to get this to work.

@hackaugusto Just to see if I follow.

You want the transport `message_id` to reflect the more "pure" protocol message id of just being a randomly generated int. Then the transport due to the `PING` message you think can have the more complicated type but should not be translated as the generic message id to the typing module. 

If we are to do so then I would also rename the `MessageID` type to `ProtocolMessageID` so that no doubt is left to the reader as to why these 2 types are different.

@nulinspiratie I was basically thinking of the differences in the intended uses between nodes and channels. Where channels are currently typically used through subclassing, nodes were intended to be created by adding  parameters with an extended `add_parameter` method. Adding, what I called "homogeneous" channels/nodes, can of course also be achieved by looping over a group of add_parameter calls and is only a question of personal preference.
There are some drivers that have channels with parameter-getters/setters that rely on channel attributes (e.g. ZNB, Decadac)

@AdriaanRol I was also wondering about the intended use of  `add_submodule`. In the main code base it is exclusively used for adding channels. Possibly this can be added to the list of concepts that can be replaced by a `ParameterNode`?

